# Patchlevel: README_1.1

The mx driver allows several IBM style serial I/O port boards connected to the
Palomax, Inc. MAX-125 interface adapter to operate under s5r4 UNIX.
Up to 8 serial ports can be added.


To integrate the mx drivers into the kernel:

log in as bin.


Make the mx directory (/usr/sys/amiga/driver/mx) and copy all of the files
in this directory to it.

Read the beginning of the mx.c file for information on configuring mx.c for
the particular IBM serial port board(s) you will be using.

The Makefl.mx.mod file contains lines tagged with "jck" to be integratred into the
/usr/sys/amiga/driver/Makefile.  (make a backup copy of the original first)

The kernel.c.mx file contains lines tagged with "jck" to be integratred into the
/usr/sys/master.d/kernel.c file.  (make a backup copy of the original first)

The ttrap.s file contains lines tagged with "jck" to be integratred into the
/usr/sys/amiga/ml/ttrap.s file.  (make a backup copy of the original first)

The Makefile builds the mx driver exp object.


Remove the following files:
/usr/sys/master.d/exp
/usr/sys/amiga/ml/exp
/usr/sys/amiga/driver/mx/exp	(when you rebuild mx)


login as root

from /usr/sys:
make   to make the new system
then:
make bootfloppy    to placing it on a floppy for testing
or:
make install     to place it on the hard disk for booting


make the following mx device nodes:
mknod /dev/term/mx0 c 47 0
mknod /dev/term/mx1 c 47 1
mknod /dev/term/mx2 c 47 2
mknod /dev/term/mx3 c 47 3
mknod /dev/term/mx4 c 47 4
mknod /dev/term/mx5 c 47 5
mknod /dev/term/mx6 c 47 6
mknod /dev/term/mx7 c 47 7

chmod 666 /dev/term/mx*


modify /etc/amiga.ap and add the entries like that of the current devices
for login ports.

# major  minor lastminor   modules
    47     0       7       ldterm   ttcompat


add the mx? ports to /etc/saf/serial/_pmtab using pmadm, etc.


reboot the new unix and your new ports should be working.


